55.8	Lignite	Lignite	Lignite, often referred to as brown coal, or Rosebud coal by Northern Pacific Railroad, is a soft brown fuel with characteristics that put it somewhere between coal and peat. It is considered the lowest rank of coal; it is mined in Germany, Poland, Kosovo, Russia, the United States, India, Australia and many European countries, and it is used almost exclusively as a fuel for steam-electric power generation. Up to 50% of Greece's electricity and 24.6% of Germany's comes from lignite power plants.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Lignite-coal.jpg/220px-Lignite-coal.jpg
